Yes, our Charleston Gardens
Restaurant is open today, ma'am,

73
00:02:18,175 --> 00:02:19,842
as it is every day.

74
00:02:19,926 --> 00:02:22,470
Oh, it's terrific.
It's some of the best food in town.

75
00:02:22,554 --> 00:02:24,847
Do not get the crab meat salad.

76
00:02:24,931 --> 00:02:26,474
The crab meat salad.

77
00:02:26,558 --> 00:02:28,102
It's Monday.
Crab's delivered on Tuesdays.

78
00:02:28,186 --> 00:02:30,145
-Do the math.
-O'TOOLE: Miriam Maisel.

79
00:02:30,229 --> 00:02:32,272
MIDGE: Oh, Mrs. O'Toole.

80
00:02:32,356 --> 00:02:33,899
I was just suggesting
things from the menu.

81
00:02:33,983 --> 00:02:35,651
Headset down. Come with me.

82
00:02:45,036 --> 00:02:46,370
Your office?

83
00:02:46,454 --> 00:02:48,080
First floor.

84
00:02:48,164 --> 00:02:49,707
First floor?

85
00:02:49,791 --> 00:02:51,500
-Makeup Department.
-You're back in the show.

86
00:02:51,584 --> 00:02:53,711
-Girls.
-B. Altman, where may I direct your call?

87
00:02:53,795 --> 00:02:57,507
Come.

88
00:02:57,591 --> 00:03:00,719
<i>♪ There'll be a change in the weather ♪</i>

89
00:03:00,803 --> 00:03:03,888
<i>♪ And a change in the sea ♪</i>

90
00:03:03,972 --> 00:03:05,640
<i>♪ From now on… ♪</i>

91
00:03:05,724 --> 00:03:07,308
It's Midge.

92
00:03:07,392 --> 00:03:10,145
Hi, Midge.

93
00:03:10,229 --> 00:03:12,313
<i>♪ My walk will be different ♪</i>

94
00:03:12,397 --> 00:03:14,524
<i>♪ My talk and my name… ♪</i>

95
00:03:14,608 --> 00:03:16,651
-I'm confused.
-You're checking coats.

96
00:03:16,735 --> 00:03:18,695
-Checking coats?
-We're short a hand

97
00:03:18,779 --> 00:03:20,697
and you're the most
presentable of the basement girls.

98
00:03:20,781 --> 00:03:22,366
Is this a problem?

99
00:03:22,450 --> 00:03:25,661
No. Not at all.
Thank you, but I… I was just thinking

100
00:03:25,745 --> 00:03:27,955
I would be so much more
valuable behind the makeup counter.

101
00:03:28,039 --> 00:03:30,291
-I need you here.
-I've kept up with all the latest

102
00:03:30,375 --> 00:03:31,834
styles and trends since
I've been off the floor.

103
00:03:31,918 --> 00:03:34,670
Face masks, they're
the future and the past.

104
00:03:34,754 --> 00:03:36,255
Cleopatra used them.
Isn't that interesting?

105
00:03:36,339 --> 00:03:38,549
-Lake mud and egg whites.
-I need you here.

106
00:03:38,633 --> 00:03:41,010
Well, I've never been
trained for coat check.

107
00:03:41,094 --> 00:03:43,387
Take coat, give ticket.
Take ticket, give coat.

108
00:03:43,471 --> 00:03:45,181
Congratulations. You've been trained.

109
00:03:45,265 --> 00:03:46,766
Now, one more thing.

110
00:03:46,850 --> 00:03:49,227
And listen very closely.

111
00:03:49,311 --> 00:03:50,645
I'm listening.

112
00:03:50,729 --> 00:03:52,731
Never leave the booth.

113
00:03:52,815 --> 00:03:55,025
Yes, ma'am.

114
00:03:55,109 --> 00:03:59,404
<i>♪ There'll be some changes made. ♪</i>

115
00:03:59,488 --> 00:04:04,284
Take coat, give ticket.

116
00:04:04,368 --> 00:04:06,536
Coat room?

117
00:04:06,620 --> 00:04:09,039
Purgatory with a better view.

118
00:04:09,123 --> 00:04:10,624
-Poor thing.
-Hey, did you hear?

119
00:04:10,708 --> 00:04:12,375
-I'm not Mary's maid of honor.
-I told you, Viv,

120
00:04:12,459 --> 00:04:14,127
my sister had to be maid of honor.

121
00:04:14,211 --> 00:04:15,212
It's a family thing.

122
00:04:15,296 --> 00:04:16,631
How's planning going?

123
00:04:16,715 --> 00:04:17,715
Oh, we've had a couple of hiccups.

124
00:04:17,799 --> 00:04:18,925
Hiccups? Your sister's a bitch.

125
00:04:19,009 --> 00:04:20,760
-Viv.
-We're on the floor.

126
00:04:20,844 --> 00:04:22,553
She got a little bossy,
so I nudged her aside.

127
00:04:22,637 --> 00:04:24,013
I'm doing it all myself now.

128
00:04:24,097 --> 00:04:26,599
What?
Oh, my God, Mary, no, you can't do that.

129
00:04:26,683 --> 00:04:27,735
-O'TOOLE: Girls!
-O'Toole.

130
00:04:27,819 --> 00:04:28,142
Ooh.

131
00:04:28,226 --> 00:04:29,644
Mary, wait.

132
00:04:29,728 --> 00:04:31,354
-She'll need water.
-Got him.

133
00:04:31,438 --> 00:04:34,107
Pookie's a her.

134
00:04:34,191 --> 00:04:37,235
[WHISPERING] Mary.

135
00:04:37,319 --> 00:04:38,736
ANNOUNCER [OVER PA]: <i>Attention, ladies.</i>

136
00:04:38,820 --> 00:04:40,988
<i>Rouge Master Class begins in five minutes</i>

137
00:04:41,072 --> 00:04:43,283
<i>-at the Revlon counter.</i>
-Sweetie, I'm sorry,

138
00:04:43,367 --> 00:04:44,576
but you can't plan your
wedding by yourself.

139
00:04:44,660 --> 00:04:46,578
It's too much. Let me help.

140
00:04:46,662 --> 00:04:48,413
Oh, Midge, thank you, but there's no time

141
00:04:48,497 --> 00:04:50,415
-and really no money.
-Don't worry about money.

142
00:04:50,499 --> 00:04:52,584
What you need is experience
and I have experience.

143
00:04:52,668 --> 00:04:55,170
The marriage didn't stick, but
my reception was unforgettable.

144
00:04:55,254 --> 00:04:56,463
It got a write-up in the
<i>Jewish Daily Forward,</i>

145
00:04:56,547 --> 00:04:56,922
[GASPS]

146
00:04:57,006 --> 00:04:58,632
in Yiddish, so it didn't
get a wide readership,

147
00:04:58,716 --> 00:05:00,092
but the picture was sensational

148
00:05:00,176 --> 00:05:02,719
and I can make the
time for you, my friend.

149
00:05:02,803 --> 00:05:05,097
-I don't know.
-Please. I want to.

150
00:05:05,181 --> 00:05:08,600
No one should have a
less than perfect wedding.

151
00:05:08,684 --> 00:05:10,353
Okay. Yes. Yes!

152
00:05:10,437 --> 00:05:12,105
-Good.
-Really good.

153
00:05:12,189 --> 00:05:13,940
I'm relieved. I'll see you at lunch.

154
00:05:14,024 --> 00:05:15,525
See you at lunch.

155
00:05:20,405 --> 00:05:22,365
Look at this.

156
00:05:22,449 --> 00:05:24,117
The high ceilings, the tile floor,

157
00:05:24,201 --> 00:05:25,285
like the Vatican.

158
00:05:25,369 --> 00:05:26,661
I feel like I forgot something.

159
00:05:26,745 --> 00:05:27,829
How are we doing here, Curren?

160
00:05:27,913 --> 00:05:29,581
MOISHE: Why would a fakakta bank

161
00:05:29,665 --> 00:05:31,791
in the tuchus of Brooklyn
try to compete with the Pope?

162
00:05:31,875 --> 00:05:33,084
I need to start writing things down,

163
00:05:33,168 --> 00:05:34,502
but by the time I find a pen,

164
00:05:34,586 --> 00:05:36,463
I forget what I was
supposed to write down.

165
00:05:36,547 --> 00:05:39,216
It's so open, so flaunting, so gentile.

166
00:05:39,300 --> 00:05:40,718
Jews use the bank, too, Pop.

167
00:05:40,802 --> 00:05:42,178
Show me one. Hey.

168
00:05:42,262 --> 00:05:44,722
-You a Jew?
-Pop. Sorry.

169
00:05:44,806 --> 00:05:47,683
So, how close are we to
wrapping this up, Curren?

170
00:05:47,767 --> 00:05:49,226
Curren. What is that?

171
00:05:49,310 --> 00:05:51,353
Just making sure all
the I's are dotted here.

172
00:05:51,437 --> 00:05:51,962
He dots the I's.

173
00:05:52,046 --> 00:05:53,731
And I've got a team
counting cash in the back.

174
00:05:53,815 --> 00:05:55,482
It'll take a while.

175
00:05:55,566 --> 00:05:58,194
-Only a goy dots the I's.
-I hope it's all there.

176
00:05:58,278 --> 00:05:59,778
The treasure map's in pretty bad shape.

177
00:05:59,862 --> 00:06:00,075
Treasure map?

178
00:06:00,159 --> 00:06:01,071
JOEL: It's just what
she calls her records

179
00:06:01,155 --> 00:06:02,489
marking where she put the money.

180
00:06:02,573 --> 00:06:04,159
Ma, what… what are you looking for?

181
00:06:04,243 --> 00:06:06,286
I feel like I forgot something.

182
00:06:06,370 --> 00:06:09,372
Moishe, did you bring the bag
of money we use to bribe people?

183
00:06:09,456 --> 00:06:11,416
There's a bag of money
we use to bribe people.

184
00:06:11,500 --> 00:06:12,834
A little louder, Ma.

185
00:06:12,918 --> 00:06:14,419
I don't think they heard
you in Poughkeepsie.

186
00:06:14,503 --> 00:06:15,712
Curren, that's not a name.

187
00:06:15,796 --> 00:06:18,298
That's something you pour over rice.

188
00:06:18,382 --> 00:06:19,716
And, Pop, Mr. Cleary is
my buddy Archie's brother

189
00:06:19,800 --> 00:06:21,509
and he's doing us a big favor here.

190
00:06:21,593 --> 00:06:24,012
By taking our money?
I wish I could do someone that favor.

191
00:06:24,096 --> 00:06:26,806
-Mr. Curry, a question…
-Cleary. Cleary.

192
00:06:26,890 --> 00:06:28,892
Is there gonna be another
Great Depression soon?

193
00:06:28,976 --> 00:06:30,603
Is that something you can tell us?

194
00:06:30,687 --> 00:06:32,647
If I could, I'd be the
president of the bank

195
00:06:32,731 --> 00:06:34,065
or the United States.

196
00:06:34,149 --> 00:06:36,067
Step on enough Jews, you'll get there.

197
00:06:36,151 --> 00:06:38,903
Now I remember. I found this.

198
00:06:38,987 --> 00:06:40,988
It was behind one of the radiators.

199
00:06:41,072 --> 00:06:42,949
Ma, you said you found all the money.

200
00:06:43,033 --> 00:06:44,617
On the first treasure map.

201
00:06:44,701 --> 00:06:47,787
I found two more treasure
maps this morning.

202
00:06:47,871 --> 00:06:50,081
Oh, should we lock these up in the safe?

203
00:06:50,165 --> 00:06:51,832
They show where all our stashes are.

204
00:06:51,916 --> 00:06:54,543
-They're like gold.
-I'm in charge of these from now on.

205
00:06:54,627 --> 00:06:56,880
Are we gonna be okay?

206
00:06:58,966 --> 00:07:02,470
You… are not Jewish.

207
00:07:04,513 --> 00:07:05,847
-Thank you for shopping B. Altman.
-WOMAN: It's a little plain.

208
00:07:05,931 --> 00:07:08,016
Sometimes I just want
to spark it up a little.

209
00:07:08,100 --> 00:07:09,476
-You know?
-Mm-hmm.

210
00:07:09,560 --> 00:07:11,144
Yes, ma'am.
What's life without a little spark?

211
00:07:11,228 --> 00:07:12,562
So, what do I do? How do I do that?

212
00:07:12,646 --> 00:07:14,355
ELSA: You could go
bolder with the colors.

213
00:07:14,439 --> 00:07:14,606
Oh.

214
00:07:14,690 --> 00:07:16,400
-WOMAN: Like what?
-Fuchsia?

215
00:07:16,484 --> 00:07:17,776
-Oy.
-WOMAN: Interesting.

216
00:07:17,860 --> 00:07:20,112
-ELSA: Or maybe orange.
-Aah!

217
00:07:20,196 --> 00:07:22,406
ANNOUNCER: <i>Husbands, a
new waiting lounge has opened up</i>

218
00:07:22,490 --> 00:07:24,367
<i>on the first floor.</i>

219
00:07:24,451 --> 00:07:25,868
What the hell? You're in a box.

220
00:07:25,952 --> 00:07:27,287
Did Madame Alexander put you in there?

221
00:07:27,371 --> 00:07:28,663
I'm the coat room attendant.

222
00:07:28,747 --> 00:07:31,040
This is my job, Susie, and
I am proud of the work I do.

223
00:07:31,124 --> 00:07:34,460
-Ooh.
-Yeah, seems really soul satisfying.

224
00:07:34,544 --> 00:07:36,087
ANNOUNCER: <i>Attention, B.
Altman customers,</i>

225
00:07:36,171 --> 00:07:37,297
<i>the store will be closing in 15 minutes.</i>

226
00:07:37,381 --> 00:07:39,090
What are you doing here?

227
00:07:39,174 --> 00:07:40,216
We have a gig tonight, remember?

228
00:07:40,300 --> 00:07:41,718
Yes, but we were meeting at the club.

229
00:07:41,802 --> 00:07:42,927
This place is on the way.

230
00:07:43,011 --> 00:07:44,512
It's 20 blocks out of your way.

231
00:07:44,596 --> 00:07:46,723
And I like having extra
time with you before the gigs

232
00:07:46,807 --> 00:07:48,141
to talk, dish.

233
00:07:48,225 --> 00:07:49,767
Sammy Davis Jr.'s dating a white chick.

234
00:07:49,851 --> 00:07:51,812
You're frog-marching me to the gig.

235
00:07:51,896 --> 00:07:53,772
-That, too.
-Susie.

236
00:07:53,856 --> 00:07:55,357
We have a bunch of gigs coming up

237
00:07:55,441 --> 00:07:57,026
and I don't like standing
there with my thumb up my ass.

238
00:07:57,110 --> 00:07:59,194
I'm not always late.

239
00:07:59,278 --> 00:08:02,531
Fine. We'll go together, under protest

240
00:08:02,615 --> 00:08:05,242
because I do not appreciate
this lack of faith in my punctuality.

241
00:08:05,326 --> 00:08:07,578
-Viv, punch out for me.
-VIVIAN: You got it.

242
00:08:07,662 --> 00:08:09,580
-How may I help you?
-Not this.

243
00:08:09,664 --> 00:08:14,460
-This and this.
-Thanks.

244
00:08:14,544 --> 00:08:16,712
Not that or that.

245
00:08:16,796 --> 00:08:20,925
-This. This. Not that.
-Ah.

246
00:08:21,009 --> 00:08:22,635
