491
00:18:20,756 --> 00:18:22,298
-Sure.
-Would you ask your brother

492
00:18:22,382 --> 00:18:24,258
if real estate prices
are gonna go up or down

493
00:18:24,342 --> 00:18:25,969
in the next ten years?
That would be a big help.

494
00:18:26,053 --> 00:18:27,261
I will ask him.

495
00:18:27,345 --> 00:18:29,138
Oh, Curry is a good man.

496
00:18:29,222 --> 00:18:32,016
He's a nice blend of
spices and herbs, as well.

497
00:18:32,100 --> 00:18:34,852
Ah. Well, I'll leave you
boys to get on with things.

498
00:18:34,936 --> 00:18:36,438
Your sword fights and whatnot.

499
00:18:36,522 --> 00:18:38,065
Thank you, Mrs. Maisel.

500
00:18:38,149 --> 00:18:39,692
Thanks, Ma.

501
00:18:39,776 --> 00:18:41,485
Smells like a foxhole in here.

502
00:18:41,569 --> 00:18:43,320
-Yeah, sorry.
-Can I get some coffee?

503
00:18:43,404 --> 00:18:44,738
Coming up.

504
00:18:44,822 --> 00:18:46,532
And these are…

505
00:18:46,616 --> 00:18:47,950
My mother's treasure maps.

506
00:18:48,034 --> 00:18:49,368
Supposed to show where they've hidden

507
00:18:49,452 --> 00:18:50,661
all the cash over the years.

508
00:18:50,745 --> 00:18:52,079
-Did Curren see these?
-You bet he did.

509
00:18:52,163 --> 00:18:53,372
That's what I thought.

510
00:18:53,456 --> 00:18:55,290
He's denying us a line of credit.

511
00:18:55,374 --> 00:18:57,835
Told us there were too many
"mitigating circumstances,"

512
00:18:57,919 --> 00:18:59,878
which my father called
the two most goyish words

513
00:18:59,962 --> 00:19:01,088
in the English language.

514
00:19:01,172 --> 00:19:02,506
[SNIFFS]

515
00:19:02,590 --> 00:19:03,967
Smells like Ma's making kugel.

516
00:19:04,051 --> 00:19:05,552
She makes good kugel.

517
00:19:05,636 --> 00:19:07,387
Don't leave before you have some kugel.

518
00:19:07,471 --> 00:19:12,058
You know, Joel, you and
I are good friends. Close.

519
00:19:12,142 --> 00:19:13,893
To the point where we didn't
even correct your mother

520
00:19:13,977 --> 00:19:15,520
when she implied that
we're a couple of queers.

521
00:19:15,604 --> 00:19:18,857
And because of that, I need to say,

522
00:19:18,941 --> 00:19:21,484
you have got to get
out of this fucking house!

523
00:19:21,568 --> 00:19:23,653
Of course I have to
get out of this house!

524
00:19:23,737 --> 00:19:25,655
I mean, look at me.

525
00:19:25,739 --> 00:19:28,783
I… I'm back with my toys and
my mother and the fucking kugel

526
00:19:28,867 --> 00:19:30,786
and it wasn't supposed to be like this.

527
00:19:30,870 --> 00:19:32,455
I've got to find a place.

528
00:19:32,539 --> 00:19:34,331
And it's got to be right
for the kids, too, because

529
00:19:34,415 --> 00:19:36,751
they have to be with me
some of the time or I'll go crazy.

530
00:19:36,835 --> 00:19:38,377
Good. You still got some fight left.

531
00:19:38,461 --> 00:19:40,171
Now stop moving around.

532
00:19:40,255 --> 00:19:42,548
It's making the smell in here worse.

533
00:19:42,632 --> 00:19:44,967
[SIGHS]

534
00:19:45,051 --> 00:19:50,639
I got Curren to reconsider
the mitigating circumstances.

535
00:19:50,723 --> 00:19:52,349
You're getting your line of credit.

536
00:19:52,433 --> 00:19:54,894
-Arch. You're kidding.
-I've got things on him.

537
00:19:54,978 --> 00:19:56,562
And I vouched for you.

538
00:19:56,646 --> 00:19:58,482
And I'm gonna help you
get the hell out of here

539
00:19:58,566 --> 00:20:00,859
because it's just sad.

540
00:20:00,943 --> 00:20:02,402
I owe you, Arch.

541
00:20:02,486 --> 00:20:04,905
I owe you big-time.

542
00:20:04,989 --> 00:20:06,531
[DOOR OPENS]

543
00:20:06,615 --> 00:20:09,910
Oops. Never mind me. I saw nothing.

544
00:20:09,994 --> 00:20:11,996
[DOOR CLOSES]

545
00:20:16,167 --> 00:20:19,461
Oh. Hey, Albert, help.

546
00:20:19,545 --> 00:20:22,089
Ah.

547
00:20:22,173 --> 00:20:23,883
You're a prince, Albert.

548
00:20:23,967 --> 00:20:25,885
"Prince Albert."
I just came up with that.

549
00:20:25,969 --> 00:20:28,137
-Thank you, ma'am.
-[CLEARS THROAT]

550
00:20:28,221 --> 00:20:29,972
Hi. Midge.

551
00:20:30,056 --> 00:20:33,392
-Hi.
-Midge, let me introduce you

552
00:20:33,476 --> 00:20:36,062
to Father O'Brien, and
this is Sister Saint Stephen.

553
00:20:36,146 --> 00:20:38,481
Father, Sister, this is my
good friend Midge Maisel.

554
00:20:38,565 --> 00:20:40,358
She's here to help me with the reception.

555
00:20:40,442 --> 00:20:42,110
-Nice to meet you.
-And nice to meet you, miss.

556
00:20:42,194 --> 00:20:44,196
[GIRL CRYING]

557
00:20:45,655 --> 00:20:49,033
Carrie Ann misbehaved in geography class.

558
00:20:49,117 --> 00:20:52,454
Yes. Of course.

559
00:20:52,538 --> 00:20:54,456
Will you excuse us for just a second?

560
00:20:54,540 --> 00:20:57,084
I've got some important
business to discuss with Mary here.

561
00:20:57,168 --> 00:20:59,086
[WHISPERING]: What is this?
What is happening?

562
00:20:59,170 --> 00:21:01,421
This is my parish. I'm getting
married in the church upstairs.

563
00:21:01,505 --> 00:21:03,048
It's very old, very beautiful.

564
00:21:03,132 --> 00:21:04,967
Sure, sure, but where are we now?

565
00:21:05,051 --> 00:21:06,844
This is where the
reception's going to be.

566
00:21:06,928 --> 00:21:08,303
-In this room?
-Yes.

567
00:21:08,387 --> 00:21:10,180
-No. No. No.
-Yes. Yes.

568
00:21:10,264 --> 00:21:11,390
Mary, there's no light here.

569
00:21:11,474 --> 00:21:13,058
It's damp and lifeless.

570
00:21:13,142 --> 00:21:14,393
And there's a little
girl crying in the corner.

571
00:21:14,477 --> 00:21:16,019
This is the Punishment Room.

572
00:21:16,103 --> 00:21:17,480
You can't have your reception
in the Punishment Room.

573
00:21:17,564 --> 00:21:19,065
-Midge.
-The walls are stained with tears.

574
00:21:19,149 --> 00:21:20,525
My sister had her reception here.

575
00:21:20,609 --> 00:21:22,569
-And how happy is your sister?
-Well…

576
00:21:22,653 --> 00:21:24,696
Because she got married
in the Punishment Room.

577
00:21:24,780 --> 00:21:27,699
-Is everything okay?
-Yes, ma'am. Sir. Sister.

578
00:21:27,783 --> 00:21:30,201
There is a bigger room that
you go through to get here.

579
00:21:30,285 --> 00:21:31,411
It has a window.

580
00:21:31,495 --> 00:21:32,620
That's the Window Room.

581
00:21:32,704 --> 00:21:33,830
That's really what they call it?

582
00:21:33,914 --> 00:21:35,039
The bigger donors get that room.

583
00:21:35,123 --> 00:21:36,332
My family's not a big donor.

584
00:21:36,416 --> 00:21:37,667
Ah. So it's about money.

585
00:21:37,751 --> 00:21:39,586
Bartering. I can work with that.

586
00:21:39,670 --> 00:21:41,118
Now who's the power
here, the priest or the nun?

587
00:21:41,202 --> 00:21:41,421
Midge.

588
00:21:41,505 --> 00:21:42,798
-Mary.
-The priest.

589
00:21:44,842 --> 00:21:46,969
Father, can we talk?

590
00:21:47,053 --> 00:21:48,137
Of course, dear.

591
00:21:48,221 --> 00:21:50,139
Don't we love our sweet Mary?

592
00:21:50,223 --> 00:21:51,640
Oh, I've known Mary all her life.

593
00:21:51,724 --> 00:21:53,726
I baptized her when
she was just a week old.

594
00:21:53,810 --> 00:21:55,561
Ah, well, I'm Jewish.

595
00:21:55,645 --> 00:21:58,022
When somebody dunks
us in water, we call a lawyer.

596
00:21:58,106 --> 00:22:00,024
I was just wondering, this room

597
00:22:00,108 --> 00:22:02,651
would it be possible to
give it a coat of paint?

598
00:22:02,735 --> 00:22:03,986
Lighten it up a little?

599
00:22:04,070 --> 00:22:06,030
Father picked this color himself.

600
00:22:06,114 --> 00:22:07,489
And it's a nice one.

601
00:22:07,573 --> 00:22:10,367
Yellow mustard… gas.

602
00:22:10,451 --> 00:22:13,496
But a sky blue would
make the room feel cheerier.

603
00:22:13,580 --> 00:22:14,873
This is the Punishment Room.

604
00:22:14,957 --> 00:22:17,125
And there's no budget to paint.

605
00:22:17,209 --> 00:22:20,128
Okay. Well, do you supply flowers?

606
00:22:20,212 --> 00:22:22,756
A lot of colorful flowers
would really liven things up.

607
00:22:22,840 --> 00:22:25,258
-We have no flowers.
-There's no money for flowers.

608
00:22:25,342 --> 00:22:27,677
Well, you have flowers at funerals.

609
00:22:27,761 --> 00:22:29,262
Anyone scheduled to die the
week before Mary's wedding?

610
00:22:29,346 --> 00:22:30,472
We'll take those.

611
00:22:30,556 --> 00:22:31,973
-Mary.
-MARY: Midge…

612
00:22:32,057 --> 00:22:33,433
Is Carrie Ann still gonna be there?

613
00:22:33,517 --> 00:22:35,727
-Because that'll be very distracting.
-[CLEARS THROAT]

614
00:22:35,811 --> 00:22:38,940
Convert. Be something else.
Buddhism's nice.

615
00:22:39,024 --> 00:22:40,816
I have no choice. It is going to be here,

616
00:22:40,900 --> 00:22:42,944
in this room, at Our
Lady Of Perpetual Sorrow.

617
00:22:43,028 --> 00:22:44,779
That is not the name.

618
00:22:44,863 --> 00:22:47,490
Midge, the ceremony's the
thing, and the church is beautiful.

619
00:22:47,574 --> 00:22:49,367
Down here is just a quick breakfast,

620
00:22:49,451 --> 00:22:51,160
a splash of champagne and… what?

621
00:22:51,244 --> 00:22:53,872
-Did you say breakfast?
-Eggs and ham.

622
00:22:56,249 --> 00:22:59,377
[EXHALES]

623
00:22:59,461 --> 00:23:02,255
Mary just told me about Bill.

624
00:23:02,339 --> 00:23:03,506
About…

625
00:23:03,590 --> 00:23:05,759
Well, I guess I was the
only one not to know.

626
00:23:05,843 --> 00:23:08,387
He's a veteran of Korea. Right, Mary?

627
00:23:08,471 --> 00:23:09,972
Our brave Bill?

628
00:23:10,056 --> 00:23:11,682
Yes.

629
00:23:11,766 --> 00:23:13,517
I'd suggest we say a prayer for him now,

630
00:23:13,601 --> 00:23:15,852
but your prayers and mine, they differ.

631
00:23:15,936 --> 00:23:17,354
Mine would be <i>Mi Shebeirach.</i>

632
00:23:17,438 --> 00:23:18,939
<i>Mi Shebeirach avoteinu,</i>

633
00:23:19,023 --> 00:23:20,565
<i>Avraham, Yitzchak v'Yaakov…</i>

634
00:23:20,649 --> 00:23:21,858
You'd like a lot of our stuff, Father.

635
00:23:21,942 --> 00:23:23,777
We've got some real barnburners.

636
00:23:23,861 --> 00:23:25,862
-All right.
-But I guess what I'm wondering now is,

637
00:23:25,946 --> 00:23:28,365
what if you let them have the Window Room

638
00:23:28,449 --> 00:23:29,825
for an early evening reception?

639
00:23:29,909 --> 00:23:31,995
For just a couple of hours.
Nothing fancy.

640
00:23:32,079 --> 00:23:33,746
Our bingo ladies are there then.

641
00:23:33,830 --> 00:23:34,872
You can bump them.

642
00:23:34,956 --> 00:23:37,500
Just for this one night? For Mary?

643
00:23:37,584 --> 00:23:39,502
And Bill.

644
00:23:39,586 --> 00:23:41,337
Mary's Bill.

645
00:23:41,421 --> 00:23:45,884
-Well, we do all love Bill.
-Mm.

646
00:23:47,344 --> 00:23:49,679
I guess an early evening event

647
00:23:49,763 --> 00:23:52,223
in the Window Room can be arranged.

648
00:23:52,307 --> 00:23:54,600
Wow. So generous.

649
00:23:54,684 --> 00:23:57,020
Thanks, Father.

650
00:23:57,104 --> 00:24:00,691
I'm assuming a band
is out of the question?

651
00:24:00,775 --> 00:24:03,610
"The sandy beach
reminded Harold of picnics,

652
00:24:03,694 --> 00:24:06,613
and the thought of
picnics made him hungry."

653
00:24:06,697 --> 00:24:09,616
And just made your mommy hungry.
[CLEARS THROAT]

654
00:24:09,700 --> 00:24:13,162
"So he laid out a nice
simple picnic lunch."

655
00:24:13,246 --> 00:24:15,998
Hope he brought wine.

656
00:24:16,082 --> 00:24:20,502
"There was nothing but pie."
There's never anything but pie.

657
00:24:20,586 --> 00:24:23,089
[PHONE RINGING]

658
00:24:25,759 --> 00:24:26,885
Hello?

659
00:24:26,969 --> 00:24:28,303
I think there may be
a bag of money hidden

660
00:24:28,387 --> 00:24:29,596
in your front closet.

661
00:24:29,680 --> 00:24:31,639
-What?
<i>-I've been studying Ma's treasure maps</i>

662
00:24:31,723 --> 00:24:33,516
and one of them didn't
correspond to anywhere

663
00:24:33,600 --> 00:24:35,435
-in their house or the factory.
-Treasure maps?

664
00:24:35,519 --> 00:24:37,479
And now I think one of
them is your parents' house

665
00:24:37,563 --> 00:24:39,147
and that on one of my parents' visits,

666
00:24:39,231 --> 00:24:41,024
they stashed a bag of money in a closet.

667
00:24:41,108 --> 00:24:42,692
-I know, it sounds crazy.
-Not at all.

668
00:24:42,776 --> 00:24:44,819
Just look. It's the one in the foyer.

669
00:24:44,903 --> 00:24:46,738
Holy cow.

670
00:24:46,822 --> 00:24:49,324
I'm at the closet.

671
00:24:49,408 --> 00:24:50,658
Check the back, left side.

672
00:24:50,742 --> 00:24:53,162
Is it just gonna be sitting
in here on the floor?

673
00:24:53,246 --> 00:24:55,539
JOEL: <i>No, it's probably
in a cutout in the wall.</i>

674
00:24:55,623 --> 00:24:57,291
They cut open the wall?

675
00:24:57,375 --> 00:24:58,834
My dad has a portable rotary blade.

676
00:24:58,918 --> 00:25:00,378
This just keeps getting weirder.

677
00:25:00,462 --> 00:25:02,713
Be careful 'cause some of
the bags are booby-trapped.

678
00:25:02,797 --> 00:25:03,964
Is it gonna explode?

679
00:25:04,048 --> 00:25:06,425
There may be a mouse trap in it.
It's probably snapped.

680
00:25:06,509 --> 00:25:07,552
Unbelievable.

681
00:25:09,804 --> 00:25:13,015
-Oh, wait, the wall is jiggling.
-That must be it.

682
00:25:13,099 --> 00:25:15,727
And there's a bag.

683
00:25:19,565 --> 00:25:20,690
Found it.

684
00:25:20,774 --> 00:25:23,068
Good.
I'll come by and pick it up tomorrow.

685
00:25:23,152 --> 00:25:26,988
Joel, there must be at least $2,000 here.

686
00:25:27,072 --> 00:25:29,574
They're crazy, Midge.
My parents are crazy.

687
00:25:29,658 --> 00:25:31,868
I… I know, but at least it
skipped a generation.

688
00:25:31,952 --> 00:25:33,578
I think that's probably
all they stashed there.

689
00:25:33,662 --> 00:25:35,580
They probably got nervous
about the noise the blade made.

690
00:25:35,664 --> 00:25:37,249
One of the hazards of
secretly using power tools

691
00:25:37,333 --> 00:25:38,417
in someone else's house.

692
00:25:38,501 --> 00:25:40,836
-Kiss the kids for me?
-Okay.

693
00:25:40,920 --> 00:25:42,212
-And hug them?
-Of course.

694
00:25:42,296 --> 00:25:43,380
And tell them I'll always love them?

695
00:25:43,464 --> 00:25:44,756
Joel, are you dying?

696
00:25:44,840 --> 00:25:46,592
I've got to dig into Aunt
Golda's sub-basement tomorrow

697
00:25:46,676 --> 00:25:48,428
and there could be a
Komodo dragon guarding it.

698
00:25:48,512 --> 00:25:51,305
-Just get some sleep?
-I probably won't. Good night.

699
00:25:51,389 --> 00:25:53,975
Good night.

700
00:25:54,059 --> 00:25:56,477
DORA: I've never drawn a nude man before.

701
00:25:56,561 --> 00:25:58,146
MILLY: I've never seen a nude man before.

702
00:25:58,230 --> 00:25:59,814
Drawing a man's genitals is not easy.

703
00:25:59,898 --> 00:26:01,107
Or appetizing.

704
00:26:01,191 --> 00:26:03,067
Did you draw a face on his penis?

705
00:26:03,151 --> 00:26:05,027
-No.
-It's smiling.

706
00:26:05,111 --> 00:26:07,864
-I draw what I see.
-Rose, let's see yours.

707
00:26:07,948 --> 00:26:09,866
Oh, I completely skipped
the down-there part.

708
00:26:09,950 --> 00:26:11,409
It made me very uncomfortable.

709
00:26:11,493 --> 00:26:13,662
-Even though it was smiling?
-It's not smiling.

710
00:26:13,746 --> 00:26:15,622
I wouldn't submit that for
your master's thesis, Milly.

711
00:26:15,706 --> 00:26:17,875
A master's degree,
that sounds so important.

712
00:26:17,959 --> 00:26:19,877
-Are you all on that path?
-Pretty much.

713
00:26:19,961 --> 00:26:21,920
My, I can't even imagine.

714
00:26:22,004 --> 00:26:24,798
And once you have your
master's, what do you do with it?

715
00:26:24,882 --> 00:26:27,509
-Pardon?
-I mean, it's so audacious, a master's.

716
00:26:27,593 --> 00:26:28,719
You're learning so much.

717
00:26:28,803 --> 00:26:30,762
What are you going to
do with all that knowledge?

718
00:26:30,846 --> 00:26:33,223
-What is she talking about?
-What do you do once you graduate?

719
00:26:33,307 --> 00:26:35,225
There's a lot of things we can do. Teach.

720
00:26:35,309 --> 00:26:39,271
-Oh, yes, teach. Where?
-Here, I guess.

721
00:26:39,355 --> 00:26:41,357
But none of the teachers here are women.

722
00:26:41,441 --> 00:26:42,817
They all seem to be men.

723
00:26:42,901 --> 00:26:46,070
-I guess a lot of them are men.
-I think all of them are men.

724
00:26:46,154 --> 00:26:47,322
I never put that together.

725
00:26:47,406 --> 00:26:50,116
Some of us want to be artists.
I want to be an artist.

726
00:26:50,200 --> 00:26:53,536
But there are really no
lady artists, not in the States.

727
00:26:53,620 --> 00:26:56,331
I knew a couple back in the day in Paris.

728
00:26:56,415 --> 00:26:58,708
One quit, no one knows
where she is today.

729
00:26:58,792 --> 00:27:00,335
The other one killed herself.

730
00:27:00,419 --> 00:27:02,378
Mainly because no one
would buy art from a girl.

731
00:27:02,462 --> 00:27:04,214
She tried calling herself
Bertrum and wearing a bowler,

732
00:27:04,298 --> 00:27:05,549
but it didn't work.

733
00:27:06,592 --> 00:27:07,635
You don't like your sandwich?

734
00:27:07,719 --> 00:27:09,053
I'm not hungry anymore.

735
00:27:09,137 --> 00:27:11,180
Some of you are doing this
to find a husband, I assume?

736
00:27:11,264 --> 00:27:12,890
That's why my daughter went to college.

737
00:27:12,974 --> 00:27:15,434
Oh, sure, she wanted to
make friends and take classes,

738
00:27:15,518 --> 00:27:18,812
